{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659996"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21095"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21095"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115532"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13970"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97535"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1175"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115532"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fatigue, headache, and confusion. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with petechiae on her lower limbs. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals mild confusion but no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 85 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 25 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 10.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 150 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin 45 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate dehydrogenase 850 U/L (120-250)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaptoglobin \u0026lt;0.1 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProthrombin time 13 seconds (11-15)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time 32 seconds (25-35)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFibrinogen 3.2 g/L (2.0-4.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA peripheral blood smear is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Immune thrombocytopenia","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe peripheral blood smear shows numerous schistocytes (fragmented red blood cells), which are the hallmark of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (MAHA). This finding, combined with the clinical presentation and laboratory results, is crucial for determining the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E (TTP) is the most likely diagnosis based on the pentad of MAHA (evidenced by schistocytes, elevated LDH, elevated bilirubin, and low haptoglobin), thrombocytopenia, neurological symptoms (confusion), renal dysfunction (elevated creatinine), and fever. TTP is caused by a deficiency of ADAMTS13, a protease that cleaves von Willebrand factor, leading to microvascular thrombosis and subsequent red cell fragmentation. The normal coagulation studies (PT, APTT, and fibrinogen) also support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenia\u003C/strong\u003E (ITP) would present with isolated thrombocytopenia without evidence of haemolysis or schistocytes on blood smear. Patients with ITP typically have normal haemoglobin levels and no evidence of organ dysfunction, making this diagnosis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E (DIC) can present with MAHA and thrombocytopenia, but would typically show abnormal coagulation studies with prolonged PT and APTT, and particularly low fibrinogen. DIC is usually secondary to another condition such as sepsis, trauma, or malignancy. The normal coagulation studies, including normal fibrinogen, in this patient make DIC unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (HUS) shares features with TTP, including MAHA, thrombocytopenia, and renal dysfunction. However, HUS typically affects children, is often preceded by a diarrhoeal illness (particularly due to Shiga toxin-producing \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E), and neurological symptoms are less common. The prominent neurological symptoms in this adult patient make TTP more likely than HUS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (AIHA) presents with haemolysis but typically shows spherocytes rather than schistocytes on blood smear. AIHA is also not associated with thrombocytopenia or organ dysfunction. The direct Coombs test would be positive in AIHA, which was not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schistocytes (fragmented red blood cells) on peripheral blood smear are the hallmark of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia.","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura is characterised by the pentad of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, neurological symptoms, renal dysfunction, and fever.","Normal coagulation studies including fibrinogen help distinguish thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura from disseminated intravascular coagulation."],"references":["Uthman, Ed. Microangiopathic Hemolytic Anemia. Flikr. Accessed under license CC By 2.0: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/deed.en. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/euthman/49129314097/in/gallery-194895448@N03-72157720376886376/","Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020; Chapter 20, page 939."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97535"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21830"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21830"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WtSIPeH4SK4HDDoCWPawFacg6J4wyJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WtSIPeH4SK4HDDoCWPawFacg6J4wyJ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1371,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97535"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T11:32:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T11:32:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115532"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"re